I'm trying to use `sharp.linear` function to equalize the histogram (stretch min and max values across the entire range of levels). In my application, this removes a type of fogging and colour casting from images.

This has worked fantastically up until I came across images that have a very compressed-looking histogram for one of the channels (I'm using Photoshop here to illustrate):

![Screen Shot 2022-06-16 at 9 57 20 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8587882/174125581-ddfb3156-770c-49d3-9b88-513e9fa4f3ff.png)

The expected result after applying my `linear` function would change the histogram from something that looks compressed (see above) into something that looks evenly spread, like this:

![Screen Shot 2022-06-16 at 10 01 04 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8587882/174126266-d459ab03-f35a-417c-9499-bc052ae4b330.png)

But instead, `sharp.linear` gave me a histogram that looks like this:

![Screen Shot 2022-06-16 at 10 00 03 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8587882/174126423-3087ae26-4cae-4718-90a6-fd8ba967266d.png)

...Which left the image with a very strong blue cast:
### unexpected result
![ultramax400_1_crop  filmQ-eq_n](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8587882/174129223-e0906de4-f364-4faf-b4a8-b6ca279b7990.jpeg)

...Normally, the results would not have the cast:
### expected result
![ultramax400_1_crop](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8587882/174129634-64d89354-9890-4b20-aad7-605a6d7c1911.jpg)

...And here's the file I've been trying to process with `sharp.linear`:
### source
![ultramax400_1_crop](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8587882/174131028-8c966c2c-a07e-494e-824a-42f8636c2ef1.jpg)
(The above image is a JPEG which is not what I used with `sharp` but because GitHub doesn't allow large TIFF files, this will have to do for now — the only thing to know is that if you try to replicate my results you will see less colour depth and JPEG artifacts).

## Code
Here's how I calculate values for `sharp.linear` function:

```js
// First, I extract a single channel from an image:
const blue = await sharp(image)
      .extractChannel("blue")
      .toColorspace("b-w")
      .toBuffer();

// Then, I get stats for that channel:
const stats = await sharp(blue).stats();

// This is the function I use to calculate the values for `sharp.linear` params:
const levels = (min: number, max: number) => {
  const scale = 255 / (max - min);
  return [scale, -min * scale];
};

// I run min/max numbers I got from stats through the above function:
const linearNumbers = levels(stats.channels[0].min, stats.channels[0].max);

// The resulting numbers are then plugged into `sharp.linear` as part of the final output steps:
const result = await blue.linear(...linearNumbers);

// ...This is then repeated for each channel and saved to file (I can add the bits that do that if needed).
```

I'm also including the data I got from stats using the above code below:
```
min/max for blue channel: [ 239, 255 ]
`levels` function output with the above numbers: [ 15.9375, -3809.0625 ]

min/max for green channel [ 209, 255 ]
`levels` function output with the above numbers: [ 5.543478260869565, -1158.5869565217392 ]

min/max for red channel  [ 141, 250 ]
`levels` function output with the above numbers: [ 2.3394495412844036, -329.86238532110093 ]
```

## What I think is happening
The closest to a possible answer I got in my research is that the numbers being fed as blue channel's `sharp.linear` parameters are too extreme. Here's the source to that guess: https://github.com/libvips/libvips/issues/1607 However, this isn't helpful as I'm not sure if that's actually the case and how can I solve for this.

